column26:
Multiple Chemical Sensitivity: Involves numerous lifestyle changes to avoid chemicals; overlaps symptomatically with other controversial conditions such as chronic fatigue syndrome and fibromyalgia; and leads to increased rates of disability{#1225}
Chemical intolerance: A symptom common to several controversial conditions, that is, sick building syndrome, multiple chemical sensitivity, chronic fatigue syndrome, and fibromyalgia
Multiple Chemical Sensitivity: Complex, chronic, polysymptomatic condition that effect the CNS, musculoskeletal, gastrointestinal, respiratory and cardiac function

Multiple chemical sensitivity: Chronic polysymptomatic, multisystem condition characterized by self-reported susceptibility to illness from low levels of multiple environmental chemicals
Multiple Chemical Sensitivity: Chronic polysymptomatic, multisystem condition characterized by subjective susceptibility to low levels of a wide spectrum of environmental compounds such as petrol, perfume or pesticides
Multiple chemical sensitivity: A chronic disorder characterized by a variety of physical and psychological symptoms associated with repeated exposure to nontoxic concentrations of odorous chemicals; symptoms affect several organs, especially the central nervous system, most frequently with patients complaining of headache, irritability, and cognitive dysfunctions; the musculoskeletal, respiratory, and digestive systems are also frequently involved{#1083}
Multiple chemical sensitivity: A chronic multisystem condition characterized by self- reported susceptibility to illness following exposure to low levels of environmental chemicals{#1446}

Multiple Chemical Sensitivity: Physical effects caused by inhalation exposure of volatile organic compounds, such as formaldehyde or toluene, diffused from materials used in construction or interior design
MCS: Acquired disorder characterized by recurrent symptoms, referable to multiple organ systems, occurring in response to demonstrable exposure to many chemically unrelated compounds at doses far below those established in the general population that cause harmful effects
Narrow-sense sick house syndrome: Syndrome which has various non-specific symptoms including mucous membrane irritation, skin complaints, headache and general fatigue which are related to chemical substances{#23313}

Idiopathic environmental intolerance/multiple chemical sensitivity: A chronic polysymptomatic condition that cannot be explained by an organic disease
Idiopathic environmental intolerance/multiple chemical sensitivity: An acquired disorder with multiple recurrent symptoms, attributed to low-level exposure to various chemically unrelated sub- stances in the environment
Multiple Chemical Sensitivity: Acquired disorder with multiple recurrent symptoms, attributed to low-level exposure to various chemically unrelated substances in the environment, and not explained by an organic disease or psychiatric disorder{#5123}
Idiopathic environmental intolerance: Also known as multiple chemical sensitivity, a poorly understood condition, characterized by multiple medically unexplained or functional symptoms that are attributed to chemically unrelated substances in the environment at doses far below those toxicologically established to cause harmful effects{#1070}

Multiple Chemical Sensitivity: Acquired increase in sensitivity to airborne chemicals
Multiple Chemical Sensitivity: A multisystem syndrome; a functional somatic disorder, is characterized by physical symptoms triggered by even extremely low levels airborne chemicals such as odors, perfumes, car exhaust etc.
Multiple chemical sensitivity: A condition where patients report a range of recurrent non-specific symptoms after being exposed to low levels of chemicals commonly encountered during everyday life{#12470}

Multiple Chemical Sensitivity: A severe condition in which the sufferer experiences a complex array of regular unspecific symptoms, considered to be the brain’s response to stress or negative psychosomatic status attributed to low-level chemical exposure tolerated by most people rather than a result of toxicological effects{#12585}
Multiple Chemical Sensitivity: Nonspecific health complains due to poor indoor environmental quality{#7161}
Multiple Chemical Sensitivity: Acquired disorder with multiple recurrent symptoms, as being associated with diverse environmental factors tolerated by the majority of people, and as not being explainable by any known medical or psychiatric disorder{#7159}
